A '''hobbledehoy''' (from an old [[Scots language|Scots]] word) is an awkward rustic adolescent boy or [[teenager]]. A hobbledehoy is naïve, gawky, and shy around women. He is neither a boy nor a man, and so is also called a halfling. The root word ''hob'' is also used to describe the little men of fairy tales, like hobs, [[hobgoblin]]s, and hobyahs. 

The word hobbledehoy is used by [[Richard Hannay]] in [[John Buchan]]'s The Three Hostages to refer to the local rustics.
''The [[Hobbit]]'' (in a book by Tolkien) is a 3 foot tall man, half the height of a 6 foot man, and therefore a [[halfling]]. In [[Walt Disney Pictures|Disney]]'s ''The Legend of Sleepy Hollow'', Ichabod Crane, a tall gawky school master, is described as a hobbledehoy in a song, referring to his awkwardness.